{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ἥρως</b>, ὁ <br /> (also ἡ in <i>signification</i> 111), <i>genitive</i> ἥρωος (ἥρως codices in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 6.303, perhaps to be read ἥρω?~Xος), “IG” 22.1641.6 (4th c.BC)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], etc.; also ἥρω [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 19.249, “IG” 2.1191 (3rd c.BC), 2nd c.AD: Pausanias Periegeta 10.4.10: _dative_ ἥρωϊ\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>], mostly in form ἥρῳ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 7.453, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 8.483, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Comicus 174.18, Oracle texts cited in 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 43.66: _accusative_ ἥρωα 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 738d, “IG” 3.810 (ἥρω?~Xα “epigram Gr.” 774 (from Priene))\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; usually in form ἥρω [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “IG” 2.1058.25 (4th c.BC), 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 391d, 3rd c.BC: Apollonius Rhodius Epicus 2.766, etc., also ἥρων 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.167:—Plur., _nominative_ ἥρωες (ω?~X 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 4.58), rarely _contraction_ ἥρως, as in 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Fragmenta” 304: _dative_ ἥρωσιν 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Fragmenta - American Journal of Philology” 55, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Aves” 1485; ἡρώνεσσι 5th c.BC: Sophron Comicus 154: _accusative_ ἥρωας (ω?~X 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 1.53), rarely ἥρως, as in 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 516, 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Dem.Enc.” 4 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—<b>hero</b>, ἥρωες Δαναοί, Ἀχαιοί, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.110, 19.34; στίχας ἀνδρῶν ἡρώων 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 1.101 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἡρώων ἀγοράς, of the Phaeacians,[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7.44; ἥρῳ Δημοδόκῳ 8.483; οἱ ἡγεμόνες τῶν ἀρχαίων μόνοι ἦσαν ἥρωες, οἱ δὲ λαοὶ ἄνθρωποι 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Problemata” 932b18, but compare 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” cc. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> <b>the Fourth Age of men</b>, between δαίμονες and ἄνθρωποι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 172, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Cratylus” 398c. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> <b>heroes, as objects of worship</b>, ἥ. ἀντίθεοι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 1.53, 4.58 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἥ. θεός, of Heracles, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “N.” 3.22; but [Ἡρακλέϊ] τῷ μὲν ὡς Ὀλυμπίῳ θύουσι, τῷ δὲ ἑτέρῳ ὡς ἥρωι ἐναγίζουσι 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.44 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; Σίσυφος ἥ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6th c.BC: Theognis Elegiacus 711; twice in 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus, “Ag.” 516, “fragment” 55; once in 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus, “fragment” 446 (Lyric poetry); οὔτε θεοὺς οὔθ᾽ ἥρωας αἰσχυνθεῖσα 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 1.27 \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]; especially of <b>local deities</b>, founders of cities, patrons of tribes, etc., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.168, 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 4.87, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Lg.” [same place], 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Politica” 1332b18, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; at Athens, ἥ. ἐπώνυμοι <b>heroes</b> after whom the φυλαί were named, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Pausanias Periegeta 1.5.1, 2, compare 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 5.66 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of historical persons to whom divine honours were paid, as Brasidas at Amphipolis, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 5.11, compare 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 5.114, 7.117 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: hence,= Latin <i>divus</i>, ἥρωα ἀπεδείξατε [τὸν Αὔγουστον] [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd-3rd c.AD: Dio Cassius Historicus 56.41; also,= “Lares”, 1st c.BC: Dionysius Halicarnassensis 4.14 \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]; ὁ κατ᾽ οἰκίαν ἥ.,= <b>Lar familiaris</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work] 2. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> later,= μακαρίτης, <b>deceased</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.AD: Alciphro Epistolographus 3.37, 3rd c.AD: Heliodorus Scriptor Eroticus 7.13: _plural_, “PMag.Par.” 1.1390: frequently in Inscrr., ἥρως χρηστέ, χαῖρε “IG” 9(2).806, compare 14.223, etc.; even of women, [prev. work]9(2).961 (from Larissa), +others\">Refs 3rd c.AD+</a>]; θεοῖς ἥρωσι,= <b>Dis Manibus</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work]14.1795 (from Rome), etc.\">Refs</a>]; ὑβρίσαντας τοὺς ἥρωας τῶν τέκνων ἡμῶν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “SIG” 1243.23 (Acraeph.). \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> ἥ. ποικίλος, ={στιγματίας}, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.AD(?): Hesychius Legal icographus, 9th c.AD: Photius Legal icographus, etc. \">Refs 5th c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__IV</b></Level2> βοῦς ἥ., ={ἡγεμών}, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “IG” 22.1126.32. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__V</b></Level2> see at {Ἥρων}.","strongNumber":"G7636","accentedUnicode":"ἥρως","shortDef":"a hero","mediumDef":"a hero","stepGloss":"a hero","stepTransliteration":"hērōs","count":0,"_step_Type":"word"}]}